<ab>
39. One must also recognize typical Tree-trunks <lb/>
which are large underneath and slender as they rise upward;<lb/>
at times distinguish sparse white birches, <lb/>
Kapok and Linden, and apply yourself to<lb/>
the oak’s wrinkled bark and green cover,<lb/> 
and also the straight trunks, useful <lb/>
for tightening sails where the wind may heave;<lb/>
These are all dressed in their canopies of green.<lb/>
</ab>

<ab><margin>left-middle</margin>Of trunks and branches.</ab>
</div>

<div>
<id>p037v_4</id>

<ab>
40. To arrange the Trees well is beneficial,<lb/>
whether sparse shrubbery or a great Forest,<lb/>
some yellower, some greener. Make sure to show <lb/>
the undersides of some leaves, while not making<lb/>
leaves too small and delicate, to avoid a dry appearance.<lb/>
While painting foliage, try further<lb/>
to show how these sprigs expand erratically;<lb/>
some bend twisting upwards, others down.<lb/>
</ab>


<ab><margin>left-middle</margin>To construct Trees well.</ab>
</div>

